            <p>Hon. Joseph Blumenthal&#44;<lb/>
                Dear Sir&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>Doubtless you will share my gratification<lb/> at the success which met Joseph Hertz&#39;s efforts.  All appear to<lb/> agree that his discourse in my Synagogue was to the purpose&#44;<lb/> well conceived and well delivered.  I hope that the general ap&#45;<lb/>proval will redound to the benefit of the J. T. S.<lb/></p>
            <p>I saw the youth twice in my bed room&#44; to<lb/> which I am yet confined&#44; and he expressed himself pleased with<lb/> the attention shown him by members of my congregation.<lb/></p>
            <p>You will have received ere this my daughter&#39;s<lb/> letter&#44; enclosing one from Mr. Jacob Rothschild of Cauker City&#44;<lb/> Kansas&#44; who donated one hundred dollars to our institution&#44; with<lb/> the object of having a Hashcabah made by one of our students in<lb/> memory of his mother.<lb/></p>
            <p>I will be glad to learn that all came duly<lb/> to hand&#44; and that you officially acknowledged receipt of the gift.<lb/>  In connection with our senior class&#44; I would deem it very benefic&#45;<lb/>ial&#44; if we could enter into such arrangements by which elocution<lb/> forms part of their occasional instruction.  But of this more anon.<lb/>  Earnestly hoping to be soon allowed to resume the performance of my<lb/> duties&#44; I remain<lb/> Yours truly&#44;<lb/> S. MORAIS<lb/> Philadelphia&#44; Dec. 28&#44; 1891<lb/></p>
            </body>
